  "prompt": "What is the difference between foreign bonds and Eurobonds?",
  "response": "Foreign bonds and Eurobonds are both types of international bonds, but they have distinct characteristics and key differences:\n\n1. **Foreign Bonds**:\n   - Issued by a foreign entity in a domestic market.\n   - Denominated in the currency of the domestic market.\n   - Often subject to regulations and laws of the country where they are issued.\n   - Commonly named based on the country they are issued in (e.g., Yankee bonds in the US, Samurai bonds in Japan).\n\n2. **Eurobonds**:\n   - Issued in the international market outside the jurisdiction of any single country.\n   - Typically denominated in a currency different from the issuer's home country currency.\n   - Not governed by any specific domestic regulations (although they follow international standards).\n   - Can be issued in any currency and are issued within and traded globally.\n\n**Key Differences**:\n- **Issuance Location**: Foreign bonds are issued in a specific country\u2019s domestic market, while Eurobonds are issued in international markets.\n- **Denomination Currency**: Foreign bonds are denominated in the currency of the country where they are issued, whereas Eurobonds are generally in a currency different from the issuer\u2019s home country.\n- **Regulatory Environment**: Foreign bonds must comply with the regulations of the country in whose market they are issued, while Eurobonds operate under broader international financial norms without being subject to the laws of any single country.\n- **Naming**: Foreign bonds often have names that reflect the market of issuance (e.g., Yankee, Samurai), while Eurobonds are named for their international nature.",
